mediaNotes: hidden in mangroves, nesting area, several half-grown juveniles in area

This is a recording of one of the parents of the 3 very young chicks arriving at the nest, feeding the young(?), and then leaving the nest to alight on and remain in the branches nearby. The parent vocalized non-stop for well over 10 minutes. I only recorded a portion. At just under 4 minutes, a Blue Jay showed up just a few feet away from the parent. The parent went a little crazy, as you can hopefully hear.  I interpret the vocalizations I recorded to mean: I've arrived, I'm going to take care of you, and I'm here to defend you. I should note that after the parent left the nest, and as it continued to vocalize as crows flew overhead and another corvid (the Blue Jay) landed nearby, etc., the nestlings froze and assumed the "bittern posture." I never once saw them move.
